# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: seccomp-sandboxing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] In computing, a **process** is the instance of a computer program that is being executed by one or many threads.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Depending on the OS, a process may be made up of multiple threads of execution that execute instructions concurrently.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] While a computer program is a passive collection of instructions typically stored in a file on disk, a process is the execution of those instructions after being loaded from the disk into memory.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Several processes may be associated with the same program; for example, opening up several instances of the same program often results in more than one process being executed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Multitasking is a method to allow multiple processes to share processors (CPUs) and other system resources.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Each CPU (core) executes a single process at a time.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] However, multitasking allows each processor to switch between tasks that are being executed without having to wait for each task to finish (preemption).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] A common form of multitasking is provided by CPU's time-sharing that is a method for interleaving the execution of users' processes and threads, and even of independent kernel tasks – although the latter feature is feasible only in preemptive kernels such as Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Preemption has an important side effect for interactive processes that are given higher priority with respect to CPU-bound processes; therefore users are immediately assigned computing resources at the simple pressing of a key or when moving a mouse.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Furthermore, applications like video and music reproduction are given some kind of real-time priority, preempting any other lower priority process.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] In time-sharing systems, context switches are performed rapidly, which makes it seem like multiple processes are being executed simultaneously on the same processor.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] This seemingly-simultaneous execution of multiple processes is called concurrency.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] For security and reliability, most modern operating systems prevent direct communication between independent processes, providing strictly mediated and controlled inter-process communication.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The operating system holds most of this information about active processes in data structures called process control blocks.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Any subset of the resources, typically at least the processor state, may be associated with each of the process' threads in operating systems that support threads or *child* processes.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The operating system keeps its processes separate and allocates the resources they need, so that they are less likely to interfere with each other and cause system failures (e.g., deadlock or thrashing).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The operating system may also provide mechanisms for inter-process communication to enable processes to interact in safe and predictable ways.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] It is usual to associate a single process with a main program, and child processes with any spin-off, parallel processes, which behave like asynchronous subroutines.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] A process is said to *own* resources, of which an *image* of its program (in memory) is one such resource.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] However, in multiprocessing systems *many* processes may run off of, or share, the same reentrant program at the same location in memory, but each process is said to own its own *image* of the program.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Processes are often called "tasks" in embedded operating systems.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The sense of "process" (or task) is "something that takes up time", as opposed to "memory", which is "something that takes up space".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The above description applies to both processes managed by an operating system, and processes as defined by process calculi.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] If a process requests something for which it must wait, it will be blocked.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] When the process is in the blocked state, it is eligible for swapping to disk, but this is transparent in a virtual memory system, where regions of a process's memory may be really on disk and not in main memory at any time.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Even portions of active processes/tasks (executing programs) are eligible for swapping to disk, if the portions have not been used recently.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Not all parts of an executing program and its data have to be in physical memory for the associated process to be active.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] An operating system kernel that allows multitasking needs processes to have certain states.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Names for these states are not standardised, but they have similar functionality.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] When processes need to communicate with each other they must share parts of their address spaces or use other forms of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] For instance in a shell pipeline, the output of the first process needs to pass to the second one, and so on.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] By the early 1960s, computer control software had evolved from monitor control software, for example IBSYS, to executive control software.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Over time, computers got faster while computer time was still neither cheap nor fully utilized; such an environment made multiprogramming possible and necessary.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Multiprogramming means that several programs run concurrently.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] At first, more than one program ran on a single processor, as a result of underlying uniprocessor computer architecture, and they shared scarce and limited hardware resources; consequently, the concurrency was of a *serial* nature.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] On later systems with multiple processors, multiple programs may run concurrently in *parallel*.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Programs consist of sequences of instructions for processors.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] A single processor can run only one instruction at a time: it is impossible to run more programs at the same time.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] A program might need some resource, such as an input device, which has a large delay, or a program might start some slow operation, such as sending output to a printer.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] This would lead to processor being "idle" (unused).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] To keep the processor busy at all times, the execution of such a program is halted and the operating system switches the processor to run another program.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] To the user, it will appear that the programs run at the same time (hence the term "parallel").
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] Shortly thereafter, the notion of a "program" was expanded to the notion of an "executing program and its context".
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] The concept of a process was born, which also became necessary with the invention of re-entrant code.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/process-computing] However, with the advent of concepts such as time-sharing, computer networks, and multiple-CPU shared memory computers, the old "multiprogramming" gave way to true multitasking, multiprocessing and, later, multithreading.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/seccomp] seccomp mode is enabled via the `prctl(2)` system call using the `PR_SET_SECCOMP` argument, or (since Linux kernel 3.17) via the `seccomp(2)` system call. seccomp mode used to be enabled by writing to a file, `/proc/self/seccomp`, but this method was removed in favor of `prctl()`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/seccomp] In some kernel versions, seccomp disables the `RDTSC` x86 instruction, which returns the number of elapsed processor cycles since power-on, used for high-precision timing.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/seccomp] Some consider seccomp comparable to OpenBSD pledge(2) and FreeBSD capsicum(4).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/seccomp] seccomp was first devised by Andrea Arcangeli in January 2005 for use in public grid computing and was originally intended as a means of safely running untrusted compute-bound programs.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/seccomp] It was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 2.6.12, which was released on March 8, 2005.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In computing, a **system call** (**syscall**) is the programmatic way in which a computer program requests a service from the operating system on which it is executed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] This may include hardware-related services (for example, accessing a hard disk drive or accessing the device's camera), creation and execution of new processes, and communication with integral kernel services such as process scheduling.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] System calls provide an essential interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In most systems, system calls can only be made from userspace processes, while in some systems, OS/360 and successors for example, privileged system code also issues system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] For embedded systems, system calls typically do not change the privilege mode of the CPU.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The architecture of most modern processors, with the exception of some embedded systems, involves a security model.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] However, many applications need access to these components, so system calls are made available by the operating system to provide well-defined, safe implementations for such operations.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The operating system executes at the highest level of privilege, and allows applications to request services via system calls, which are often initiated via interrupts.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] An interrupt automatically puts the CPU into some elevated privilege level and then passes control to the kernel, which determines whether the calling program should be granted the requested service.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] If the service is granted, the kernel executes a specific set of instructions over which the calling program has no direct control, returns the privilege level to that of the calling program, and then returns control to the calling program.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Generally, systems provide a library or API that sits between normal programs and the operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] On Unix-like systems, that API is usually part of an implementation of the C library (libc), such as glibc, that provides wrapper functions for the system calls, often named the same as the system calls they invoke.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] On Windows NT, that API is part of the Native API, in the ntdll.dll library; this is an undocumented API used by implementations of the regular Windows API and directly used by some system programs on Windows.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The library's wrapper functions expose an ordinary function calling convention (a subroutine call on the assembly level) for using the system call, as well as making the system call more modular.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Here, the primary function of the wrapper is to place all the arguments to be passed to the system call in the appropriate processor registers (and maybe on the call stack as well), and also setting a unique system call number for the kernel to call.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In this way the library, which exists between the OS and the application, increases portability.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The call to the library function itself does not cause a switch to kernel mode and is usually a normal subroutine call (using, for example, a "CALL" assembly instruction in some Instruction set architectures (ISAs)).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The actual system call does transfer control to the kernel (and is more implementation-dependent and platform-dependent than the library call abstracting it).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] For example, in Unix-like systems, `fork` and `execve` are C library functions that in turn execute instructions that invoke the `fork` and `exec` system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] On exokernel based systems, the library is especially important as an intermediary.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] On exokernels, libraries shield user applications from the very low level kernel API, and provide abstractions and resource management.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] IBM's OS/360, DOS/360 and TSS/360 implement most system calls through a library of assembly language macros, although there are a few services with a call linkage.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] This reflects their origin at a time when programming in assembly language was more common than high-level language usage.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] IBM system calls were therefore not directly executable by high-level language programs, but required a callable assembly language wrapper subroutine.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Since then, IBM has added many services that can be called from high level languages in, e.g., z/OS and z/VSE.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In more recent release of MVS/SP and in all later MVS versions, some system call macros generate Program Call (PC).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] On Unix, Unix-like and other POSIX-compliant operating systems, popular system calls are `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `wait`, `exec`, `fork`, `exit`, and `kill`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Many modern operating systems have hundreds of system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] For example, Linux and OpenBSD each have over 300 different calls, NetBSD has close to 500, FreeBSD has over 500, Windows has close to 2000, divided between win32k (graphical) and ntdll (core) system calls while Plan 9 has 54.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Tools such as strace, ftrace and truss allow a process to execute from start and report all system calls the process invokes, or can attach to an already running process and intercept any system call made by the said process if the operation does not violate the permissions of the user.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] This special ability of the program is usually also implemented with system calls such as ptrace or system calls on files in procfs.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Implementing system calls requires a transfer of control from user space to kernel space, which involves some sort of architecture-specific feature.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] A typical way to implement this is to use a software interrupt or trap.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Interrupts transfer control to the operating system kernel, so software simply needs to set up some register with the system call number needed, and execute the software interrupt.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] This is the only technique provided for many RISC processors, but CISC architectures such as x86 support additional techniques.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] For example, the x86 instruction set contains the instructions `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` and `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` (these two mechanisms were independently created by AMD and Intel, respectively, but in essence they do the same thing).
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] These are "fast" control transfer instructions that are designed to quickly transfer control to the kernel for a system call without the overhead of an interrupt.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Linux 2.5 began using this on the x86, where available; formerly it used the `INT` instruction, where the system call number was placed in the `EAX` register before interrupt 0x80 was executed.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] An older mechanism is the call gate; originally used in Multics and later, for example, see call gate on the Intel x86.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] It allows a program to call a kernel function directly using a safe control transfer mechanism, which the operating system sets up in advance.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] For IA-64 architecture, `EPC` (Enter Privileged Code) instruction is used.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The first eight system call arguments are passed in registers, and the rest are passed on the stack.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In the IBM System/360 mainframe family, and its successors, a Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), with the number in the instruction rather than in a register, implements a system call for legacy facilities in most of IBM's own operating systems, and for all system calls in Linux.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In later versions of MVS, IBM uses the Program Call (PC) instruction for many newer facilities.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In particular, PC is used when the caller might be in Service Request Block (SRB) mode.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The PDP-11 minicomputer used the EMT, TRAP and IOT instructions, which, similar to the IBM System/360 SVC and x86 INT, put the code in the instruction; they generate interrupts to specific addresses, transferring control to the operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The VAX 32-bit successor to the PDP-11 series used the CHMK, CHME, and CHMS instructions to make system calls to privileged code at various levels; the code is an argument to the instruction.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] Within the RISC-V privileged architecture, the instruction `ECALL` (after *environment call*) is designed to enter a more privileged level and therefore this instruction performs the functionalities related to system calls.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] `ECALL` events are then handled in a similar fashion to other types of synchronous traps, including the same return mechanism.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In the related Linux implementations, the system call number is placed into the `a7` (`x17`) register before `ECALL` is executed, function arguments are listed in accordance to the RISC-V ABI (`a0`, `a1`, ...) while the return value is put in `a0`.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] System calls in most Unix-like systems are processed in kernel mode, which is accomplished by changing the processor execution mode to a more privileged one, but no *process* context switch is necessary – although a *privilege* context switch does occur.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The hardware sees the world in terms of the execution mode according to the processor status register, and processes are an abstraction provided by the operating system.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] A system call does not generally require a context switch to another process; instead, it is processed in the context of whichever process invoked it.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] In a multithreaded process, system calls can be made from multiple threads.
[src:seccomp-sandboxing/system-call] The handling of such calls is dependent on the design of the specific operating system kernel and the application runtime environment.
